\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Mixture models provide a probabilistic way to cluster data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The key idea is to associate to each data point 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

 a cluster indicator variable 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{n}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The cluster indicator serves to choose which parameter generated the data
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Generic mixture model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
A generic mixture model with 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 components (clusters) is as follows
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\boldsymbol{\kappa} & \in & \mathbb{R}_{+}^{K}\\
\boldsymbol{\rho|\boldsymbol{\kappa}} & \sim & \text{Dirichlet}(\cdot|\boldsymbol{\kappa})\\
z_{n}|\boldsymbol{\rho} & \sim & \text{Categorical}(\cdot|\boldsymbol{\rho})\\
\theta_{k} & \sim & G(\cdot)\\
x_{n}|z_{n},\boldsymbol{\theta} & \sim & F(\cdot|\theta_{k})
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 are arbitrary distributions.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Improving the model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
The main idea is to share the cellular prevalences by making them the parameters
 of the mixture distribution.
 Each cluster then represents a set of mutations which share the same evolutiona
ry history.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\boldsymbol{\rho|\boldsymbol{\kappa}} & \sim & \text{Dirichlet}(\cdot|\boldsymbol{\kappa})\\
z_{n}|\boldsymbol{\rho} & \sim & \text{Categorical}(\cdot|\boldsymbol{\rho})\\
\phi_{k} & \sim & \text{Uniform}(\cdot|[0,1])\\
b_{n}|d_{n},\boldsymbol{\phi},\boldsymbol{\pi}_{n},t,z_{n} & \sim & \sum_{\boldsymbol{\psi}}\pi_{\boldsymbol{\psi}}\text{Binomial}(b|d,\xi(\boldsymbol{\psi},\phi_{z_{n}},t))
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
MCMC inference
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
We can no longer integrate all the variables to compute the posterior.
 We could use EM to compute MAP estimates.
 However, it is useful to quantify uncertainty in this problem so we will
 do full MCMC inference.
 To update the parameters we use the following strategy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Update 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{k}$
\end_inset

 with an MH move
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Update 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{n}$
\end_inset

 with a Gibbs sampler
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Update 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\rho}$
\end_inset

 with a Gibbs sampler
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Updating the 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{n}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
The most complicated update is for the cluster indicators.
 To derive the Gibbs update we need to compute the conditional distribution
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{n}$
\end_inset

 given all the other parameters.
 This has the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
p(z_{n}=k|-) & = & \frac{\rho_{k}p(b_{n}|d_{n},\boldsymbol{\phi},\boldsymbol{\pi}_{n},t,z_{n}=k)}{\sum_{\ell}\rho_{\ell}p(b_{n}|d_{n},\boldsymbol{\phi},\boldsymbol{\pi}_{n},t,z_{n}=\ell)}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Block
\begin_inset Argument 2
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Question
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Block
How do we set the number of clusters?
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A different view of mixture models
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Note that in a mixture model if 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i}=z_{j}$
\end_inset

, then we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{z_{i}}=\theta_{z_{j}}$
\end_inset

 that is data point 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 share the same parameter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Instead of explicitly tracking the indicators we could instead assign each
 data point it own 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i}=\theta_{j}$
\end_inset

 we say 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 are in the same cluster.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Now if 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i}\sim G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a continuous distribution, there is zero probability of sharing parameters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Implicitly a mixture model solves this by constructing a discrete 
\begin_inset Formula $G(\cdot)=\sum_{k=1}^{K}\rho_{k}\delta_{\theta_{k}}(\cdot)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Dirichlet process
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The Dirichlet process (DP) is a non-parametric Bayesian prior.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Formally it is a distribution over distributions, or a stochastic process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There are two parameters to a DP: 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 the concentration and 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{0}$
\end_inset

 the base measure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 roughly controls the number of clusters
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $G_{0}$
\end_inset

 controls where the cluster parameters are located.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If we have 
\begin_inset Formula $G\sim\text{DP}(\cdot|\alpha,G_{0})$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is almost surely discrete.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Dirichlet process mixture models
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The last two slides suggest a way to use the DP to estimate the number of
 clusters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In the finite case we set 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 to have 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 components, and update the mix-weights 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{k}$
\end_inset

 and cluster parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{k}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If we instead sample 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 from a DP then the number of components 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 will be random.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Thus we can learn the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Non-parametric model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
G_{0} & = & \text{Uniform}(\cdot|[0,1])\\
G|\alpha,G_{0} & \sim & \text{DP}(\cdot|\alpha,G_{0})\\
\phi_{n}|G & \sim & G\\
b_{n}|d_{n},\phi_{n},\boldsymbol{\pi}_{n},t & \sim & \sum_{\boldsymbol{\psi}}\pi_{n\boldsymbol{\psi}}\text{Binomial}(b|d,\xi(\boldsymbol{\psi},\phi_{n},t))
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
